===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fr|en}} {{term|lang=fr|solidarité||solidarity}}, from {{term|lang=fr|solidaire||characterized by solidarity}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|lang=la|solidum||whole sum}}, neuter of {{term|lang=la|solidus||solid}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~|solidarities}}

# {{context|countable|lang=en}} A [[bond]] of [[unity]] or agreement between individuals, united around a [[common]] [[goal]] or against a common enemy, such as the unifying principle that defines the [[labor]] movement; mutual support within a group.
#: ''A long time union member himself, Phil showed '''solidarity''' with the picketing grocery store workers by shopping at a competing, unionized store.''
# {{context|uncountable|lang=en}} Willingness to give psychological and/or material [[support]] when another person is in a difficult position or needs affection.
#: ''Only the '''solidarity''' provided by her siblings allowed Margaret to cope with her mother's harrowing death.''

